Are you having trouble concentrating? 🧐🤨Trouble remembering things? 😰Do you feel weak and tired more often than usual?😪😧
If so, you might be suffering from vitamin B12 deficiency.🤷‍♀️
The first sign of vitamin B12 deficiency may appear on your skin.🧏‍♀️ You're not alone: vitamin B12 deficiency is one of the most common vitamin deficiencies we all face🫣. It can cause impair your nerves, affect your memory🧠 and thinking 🤔, and also have harmful effects on your skin👀.
Fortunately, there are a few things that you can do to combat this problem before it gets out of hand: eat your way to better skin! ☺️ Sometimes the simplest solutions are the best ones.🫶 Vitamin B12 deficiency is easy to treat with diet and vitamin supplements. Eating healthy foods 🥗🍵and taking vitamin supplements 💊 can help you avoid this issue in the future🔮. If you notice any changes in your skin, Call your dermatologist 👩🏻‍⚕️ so they can help manage them before they become serious skin problems! 😇

Acne sucks😖. We've all been there: you wake up with a breakout and think, "Oh no! I have to cover that up🥲." Well, I'm telling you: It just gets worse when you cover up a pimple😱.
Certain ingredients in makeup can further clog pores, which can lead to an increased duration of a breakout😶.
When open pimples have disrupted the skin barrier, any makeup applied to the area may get into deeper levels of exposed tissue than the product is designed to reach🫤. The result has been irritation with redness and swelling of the pimple🥵. If you're brave enough to go makeup-free for the short term in order to gain better skin in the long term, it will be good🤗.
Acne is caused by hormones, oil production, and inflammatory bacteria🦠. If you are already predisposed to breakouts, makeup can make it worse—particularly oil- or liquid-based foundations🧴.
Acne cosmetica occurs when makeup is the main source of an acne issue even though there are no others🫣. It usually appears as many tiny bumps on the cheeks, chin, and forehead🙆🏻‍♀️. As new blemishes form, you may treat pimples and then cover them with the very same makeup that caused them to appear in the first place - which leads to an ongoing frustrating cycle of pesky breakouts that are ultimately untreated🙇🏻‍♀️. Powders may increase pore clogging and primers can often increase acne inflammation🧏🏻‍♀️.
Whether or not you decide to cover your zits with makeup🙂, I strongly suggest treating the breakout first, including washing your makeup off before hitting the bed. It all starts with good habits🤗; wash your face before sleeping and if you notice your skin is beginning to act up, then take a step back and use less makeup👌🏻.

Share this with someone who needs to stop covering up the pimple😉!

And don't worry: Your skincare routine doesn't have to be complicated if you don't want it to be😇. Your morning routine should include those basics 😌: washing with a cleanser, slathering on a moisturizer, then putting on your sunscreen🤫.

"Confused between these two Judwaa? 🤔"
The difference between dry skin and dehydrated skin?
Well, here's what you need to lookout to identify if your skin is dry or dehydrated:
1. Dry skin: 
- Feels dry and itchy due to lack of sebum (oil that is naturally secreted from skin pores)
- Not just dry over the skin that surrounds the face, but also dry over the scalp, fingers and feet
- Early signs of aging are predominant
- Dry skin is in desperate need of lipid-rich skincare ingredients such as ceramides, lipids  and fatty acids
2. Dehydrated skin: 
- Looks dull due to lack of water
- Feels oily and dry despite the constant use of skincare products
- Breakouts are a common and a recurring factor
- Dehydrated skin desperately needs water-binding skincare ingredients such as Butylene Glycol, Glyceryl Sterate, Triethanolamine, etc. 
3. Dry and Dehydrated Skin: Common, visible signs to look out for are itchiness, tightness, dullness, flaky and sensitive.

Good News! If you’re not using retinol… your skin is NOT doomed! ✨

Retinol is a great ingredient – no doubt. It’s often called the gold standard for anti-ageing, pigmentation, and cell turnover. But that doesn’t mean it’s for everyone. Let's break down the hype around retinol, who shouldn’t be using it, and remember that social media trends aren't prescriptions.

If your skin barrier is compromised, or you're dealing with sensitivity, dryness or rosacea, skip the retinol and explore these gentler alternatives👇🏼

- Niacinamide (Vitamin B3)
- Azelaic Acid
- Ceramides
- Peptides
- Polyhydroxy Acids (PHAs)
